library('rjson') library('tidyverse') library('janitor') library('lubridate') library('ggplot2') library('scales') library('ggpmisc') dados_json_mortos <- fromJSON(file = "https://api.covid19api.com/country/brazil/status/deaths") dados_json_casos <- fromJSON(file = "https://api.covid19api.com/country/brazil/status/confirmed") # dados_json_curados <- fromJSON(file = "https://api.covid19api.com/country/brazil/status/recovered") json2tibble <- function(data) { mapply(as.data.frame, data, SIMPLIFY = FALSE) %>% do.call(rbind, .) %>% clean_names %>% as_tibble %>% mutate(data = ymd(substr(date, 0, 10))) %>% group_by(data) %>% summarise(cases = max(cases)) %>% ungroup() %>% mutate(novos = c('+0', paste0('+', diff(cases))), novos = ifelse(novos == '+0', '', novos)) %>% subset(cases > 0) } dados_mortos <- json2tibble(dados_json_mortos) %>% mutate(stat = 'Mortes') dados_casos <- json2tibble(dados_json_casos) %>% mutate(stat = 'Confirmados') # dados_curados <- json2tibble(dados_json_curados) %>% mutate(stat = 'Curados') dados <- do.call(rbind, list(dados_mortos, dados_casos)) dados %>% ggplot(aes(x = data, y = cases, label = novos, group = stat)) + geom_step(aes(color = stat)) + geom_text(vjust = -.25, hjust = 1) + scale_color_hue('') + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = 'top') + scale_x_date(labels = label_date_short(), breaks = breaks_width("2 days")) + scale_y_continuous(labels = label_number(big.mark = '.', decimal.mark = ',')) + ylab('Casos') + xlab('Data') + labs(title = 'Casos de COVID-19 no Brasil', caption = 'Fonte: https://covid19api.com/', subtitle = sprintf('Data de elaboração: %s', format(Sys.Date(), format = '%d/%m/%Y'))) + annotate(geom = "table", label = list(dados %>% arrange(data) %>% group_by(stat) %>% do(tail(., 1)) %>% mutate(casos = format(cases, big.mark = '.', decimal.mark = ',')) %>% select(Casos = stat, Quantidade = casos)), x = min(dados$data), y = max(dados$cases), vjust = 1, hjust = 0)

ECLIPSE

http://siddharathadhumale.blogspot.com/2019/07/how-to-upload-new-created-projet-in.html

1- Create gitbub account 2- Create new repository on that github account 3- From Eclipse first go to GIT prospective 4- Try to clone the empty *.git repository in step-2 5- Then import above step 4 repositories in our Eclipse Workspace project 6- Copy all the code which we want to upload to the git in that newly imported project in eclipse work space 7- Refresh the project/clone project ui in GIT prospective in eclipse. We will be able to see all the code in it. 8- Run the following command from project space right click project--> Team --> Synchronized work space 9- Refresh the the project/clone project ui in GIT prospective in eclipse. 10- Open GIT Staging from Eclipse Quick Access 11- Enter the comments and push the code to GIT.

GErador de aplicação

http://siddharathadhumale.blogspot.com/2019/07/how-to-upload-new-created-projet-in.html

1- Create gitbub account 2- Create new repository on that github account 3- From Eclipse first go to GIT prospective 4- Try to clone the empty *.git repository in step-2 5- Then import above step 4 repositories in our Eclipse Workspace project 6- Copy all the code which we want to upload to the git in that newly imported project in eclipse work space 7- Refresh the project/clone project ui in GIT prospective in eclipse. We will be able to see all the code in it. 8- Run the following command from project space right click project--> Team --> Synchronized work space 9- Refresh the the project/clone project ui in GIT prospective in eclipse. 10- Open GIT Staging from Eclipse Quick Access 11- Enter the comments and push the code to GIT.

Top 100 of the Best (Useful) OpenSource Applications

The following is a list of about 100 of the best OpenSource Applications, that actually help make Linux more usable for people. It is my hope that this list shows potential Linux users that there really is a large, effective, productive and usable range of free, OpenSource applications. For existing Linux users (like myself), I think this will provide a great resource in finding applications that may better suit your needs, or just for fun! Needless to say, this is just some of the thousands of applications available! I develop web sites, so this list tends to focus on applications which support that type of work.

library('rjson') library('tidyverse') library('janitor') library('lubridate') library('ggplot2') library('scales') library('ggpmisc') dados_json_mortos <- fromJSON(file = "https://api.covid19api.com/country/brazil/status/deaths") dados_json_casos <- fromJSON(file = "https://api.covid19api.com/country/brazil/status/confirmed") # dados_json_curados <- fromJSON(file = "https://api.covid19api.com/country/brazil/status/recovered") json2tibble <- function(data) { mapply(as.data.frame, data, SIMPLIFY = FALSE) %>% do.call(rbind, .) %>% clean_names %>% as_tibble %>% mutate(data = ymd(substr(date, 0, 10))) %>% group_by(data) %>% summarise(cases = max(cases)) %>% ungroup() %>% mutate(novos = c('+0', paste0('+', diff(cases))), novos = ifelse(novos == '+0', '', novos)) %>% subset(cases > 0) } dados_mortos <- json2tibble(dados_json_mortos) %>% mutate(stat = 'Mortes') dados_casos <- json2tibble(dados_json_casos) %>% mutate(stat = 'Confirmados') # dados_curados <- json2tibble(dados_json_curados) %>% mutate(stat = 'Curados') dados <- do.call(rbind, list(dados_mortos, dados_casos)) dados %>% ggplot(aes(x = data, y = cases, label = novos, group = stat)) + geom_step(aes(color = stat)) + geom_text(vjust = -.25, hjust = 1) + scale_color_hue('') + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = 'top') + scale_x_date(labels = label_date_short(), breaks = breaks_width("2 days")) + scale_y_continuous(labels = label_number(big.mark = '.', decimal.mark = ',')) + ylab('Casos') + xlab('Data') + labs(title = 'Casos de COVID-19 no Brasil', caption = 'Fonte: https://covid19api.com/', subtitle = sprintf('Data de elaboração: %s', format(Sys.Date(), format = '%d/%m/%Y'))) + annotate(geom = "table", label = list(dados %>% arrange(data) %>% group_by(stat) %>% do(tail(., 1)) %>% mutate(casos = format(cases, big.mark = '.', decimal.mark = ',')) %>% select(Casos = stat, Quantidade = casos)), x = min(dados$data), y = max(dados$cases), vjust = 1, hjust = 0)
